{
  "texts": [
    "In the last line, we ignore the iε in the denominator D 1, since it cannot vanish.",
    "When summing up these contributions, it matters whether the coefficient c i of the considered integral G A i is odd or even in the pi.",
    "As a first illustration, let us consider a numerator which is even and scales like the superclassical pentagon numerator:c i = p4 1 p4 2 = m4 1 m42.",
    "The contribution of c i G i to the time-ordered amplitude (5.3) is then the sum of the first four lines in (5.21), which simplifies at leading power toiM[p 4 1 p4 2 G i] eik, m3 1 m3 2 = -4π 2 d ¯Dℓ D 1 D 3 D 4 δ(2ℓ • v1)δ(2ℓ • v2).",
    "(5.22)For the in-in expectation value, we similarly sum up all five lines and now find a simple zero:Exp k [p 4 1 p4 2 G i] eik, m3 1 m3 2 = 0."
  ]
}